?topicID=319.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: </span><hr size=1> The plasma pulses produced by orion pulse unit explosions<br>
 will never be in contact with the pusher plate after hitting it for more then a miniscule fraction of a second.This is because of a physical principle in physics known as displacement.<br>
Here is a simple example of this principle in action on earth.<br>
I have a flat brick, or cinder block in my front yard.<br>
I also have a water hose in my yard. I set this block , or<br>
brick up in my yard. I turn the water on at full power, and I constrict it by pinching it with my fingers. As a result I cause a spurt of this water to come out of the hose at 60 miles per hour which is 30 meters a second. I aim this water at the brick or block. When the water spurt hits the brick or the block the force of the water spurt will cause the displacement of the part of the water spurt that has hit the block already.<br>
As a result all the water spurt will hit the block or the brick in an elastic collision with it and then it will rebound from the brick while transferring its momentum to it. As a result each spurt of  the water will bounce off the brick or block, and it will be in contact with for just a tiny fraction of a second. <br>
When Then when  the plasma shock wave from the detonation of all the  orion pulse units hit the pusher plate it will be an elastic collision, and it will rebound (bounce off it) after the collision with it just like the water spurts described above.<br>
This is very fundamental physics in action  Sherlock!.<br>
Tim<br>
