<br>
You are not the sole arbiter of &quot;intelligent and relevant&quot;. I am getting very bored with your little authoritarian mind game, 'Stang. &quot;Beyond the shadow of a doubt&quot;, as you judge it, is not the test here; and it could not be met without an actual vehicle being launched. It is disengenuous and irrational to introduce such a standard then demand that it be satisfied merely by discussion. &quot;A reasonable certainty&quot; is the appropriate test, and that has been met to the satisfaction of Freeman Dyson, Theodore Taylor, and many others whose judgment can reasonably be questioned only with the most extraordinary evidence in support. <br>
You have yet to even address the question for which you have the burden of proof: does the pusher plate absorb enough thermal radiation to weaken the structure to the point at which it will no longer function? Can you cite even one qualified nuclear physicist who claims that this is the case and who supports that claim with a peer-reviewed paper? We have demonstrated, if nothing else, that Orion is well-known and well-understood in the scientific community. If such an obvious objection were valid, we would see it proven chapter and verse. <br>
The board members have answered each of your objections and they have exposed your ignorance on a number of points, most especially the dynamic elasticity of the shock front. In turn you have posted little more than a series of arrogant dismissals and self-referenced appeals to authority attacking their qualifications. The facts, alone, are qualification enough but we have the recognized authorities on our side as well. If you knew anything about science, you would know that. <br>
<br>
Peer-reviewed sources:<br>
&quot;Nuclear Pulse Propulsion (Project Orion) Technical Summary Report&quot; RTD-TDR-63-3006 (1963-1964); GA-4805 Vol. 1, Reference Vehicle Design Study; Vol. 2, Interaction Effects; Vol. 3, Pulse Systems; Vol. 4, Experimental Structural Response. (From the National Technical Information Service, U.S.A.) <br>
<br>
&quot;Nuclear Pulse Propulsion (Project Orion) Technical Summary Report&quot; 1 July 1963- 30 June 1964, WL-TDR-64-93; GA-5386 Vol. 1, Summary Report; Vol. 2, Theoretical and Experimental Physics; Vol. 3, Engine Design, Analysis and Development Techniques; Vol. 4, Engineering Experimental Tests. (From the National Technical Information Service, U.S.A.) <br>
<br>
Addendum: It is interesting to note that <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.thebulletin.org/issues/1995/nd95/nd95.schwartz.html">this article</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> in the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> dismisses the Orion spacecraft as a &quot;nuclear gimcrack&quot; but does not question its technical feasibility.<br>
